# Operating Doctrine

How we build, repair, and maintain Trellis. The rules we operate by.

---

## The philosophy

A home is not built once. It is built every day. Trellis is the same.

Every feature we ship is a commitment we make to every family who uses
the product. Every repair we make has the potential to make things
worse, not better.

We build slow because we build for the long road. We repair carefully
because every repair is a trauma to the system. We change only what
must change.

This doctrine exists because we've learned the hard way that velocity
without discipline produces fragile software. Five paying families on
May 25 deserve a product that works, not a product that mostly works
when no one is looking.

---

## The five rules

### 1. Nothing ships without testing

"It typechecks" is not "it works."
"It works on my machine" is not "it works for users."

Before any code touches main:
- Run it locally against real-ish data
- For schema changes: apply the migration in a test environment first
- For UI changes: check it in both dark and light mode
- For changes to integrations (Google, Anthropic, Stripe, Supabase):
  verify the integration still works end-to-end
- For changes to authentication or authorization: log in as TWO different
  users to confirm isolation

The pattern: feature branch → push to GitHub → Vercel preview deploy →
test on the preview URL → only then merge to main.

### 2. One change at a time

No more than one customer-visible change shipped per day.
No more than one schema migration applied per day.
No more than one new integration added per week.

When the urge strikes to "while I'm in here, also fix X," resist. Ship
the one change. Confirm it works. Come back for X tomorrow.

This rule exists because compound changes hide their bugs in each
other. When three things ship together and something breaks, you can't
tell which thing broke it.

### 3. Every change must be reversible

Every commit lands as its own commit so it can be reverted alone.
Every migration must be additive (new tables, new columns) — never
destructive (renames, drops, type changes) without a multi-step plan.
Every feature flag must default to OFF for existing users.
No "while we're at it" cleanups bundled with shipping work.

If you can't undo a change cleanly, you've committed to keeping it
forever. Most of the time, that's not what you actually want.

### 4. Small radius, always

A bug fix that touches 1 file is trusted.
A bug fix that touches 5 files needs review.
A bug fix that touches 10+ files is a red flag — pause and ask whether
you're solving the right problem.

Same for features. If a feature requires sweeping changes across the
codebase, the design is probably wrong. Find a smaller version.

The Stewart Brand principle: every repair is a trauma to the system.
Smaller radius, smaller trauma.

### 5. Preserve optionality

Don't lock in decisions you don't need to make yet.
Default to feature flags for anything significant.
Default to additive schemas over destructive ones.
Defer naming, branding, and architectural decisions until they must
be made.

A decision deferred is a decision that can be made with more
information. A decision locked in early is a decision that constrains
every future decision.

